===Etymology 1===
From {{etyl|fr|en}} {{term|investir|lang=fr}}, from {{etyl|la|en}} {{term|investio||lang=la|to clothe, cover}}, from {{term|in-||in, on}} + {{term|vestio||to clothe, dress}}, from {{term|vestis||clothing}}; see [[vest]].

====Verb====
{{en-verb}}

# {{context|dated|lang=en}} To [[clothe]] or [[wrap]] (with garments).
#* '''1851''', Herman Melville, ''Moby-Dick'':
#*: He was but shabbily apparelled in faded jacket and patched trowsers; a rag of a black handkerchief '''investing''' his neck.
# {{context|obsolete|lang=en}} To [[put on]] (clothing).
#* Spenser
#*: cannot find one this girdle to '''invest'''
# To [[envelop]], [[wrap]], [[cover]].
#* '''1667''': Night / '''Invests''' the Sea, and wished Morn delayes — John Milton, ''Paradise Lost'', Book 1, ll. 207-8
# To [[commit]] [[money]] or [[capital]] in the [[hope]] of [[financial]] [[gain]].
# To spend money, [[time]], or [[energy]] into something, especially for some [[benefit]] or [[purpose]].
#: ''We'd like to thank all the contributors who have '''invested''' countless hours into this event.''
# To [[ceremonially]] [[install]] someone in some [[office]].
# To [[formally]] give (someone) some [[power]] or [[authority]].
#* Shakespeare
#*: I do '''invest''' you jointly with my power.
# To [[formally]] give (power or authority).
#* Francis Bacon
#*: It '''investeth''' a right of government.
# To surround, accompany, or attend.
#* Hawthorne
#*: awe such as must always '''invest''' the spectacle of the guilt
# To lay [[siege]] to.
#: ''to '''invest''' a town''
# {{context|intransitive|lang=en}} To make [[investments]].
# {{context|metallurgy|lang=en}} To prepare for [[lost wax]] casting by creating an investment mold (a mixture of a silica sand and plaster).

